<Post title="Why Curriculum Learning Was Essential" date="April 2026" activeTab="learned">
  <p>
    When I first started training, I threw the agent into the full game — all cards,
    all enemies, random decks. It learned nothing useful after thousands of episodes.
  </p>

  <h2>The Problem</h2>
  <p>
    With 80+ possible cards in the deck and 30+ different enemies, the state space
    was enormous. The agent couldn't even learn that "playing Strike deals damage"
    because it was drowning in complexity. Random decks meant it rarely saw the same
    card twice, so it couldn't build associations.
  </p>

  <h2>Staged Curriculum</h2>
  <p>
    I broke training into 13 stages. Stage 0 uses only the starter deck (Strikes,
    Defends, Neutralize, Survivor) against a single weak enemy. The agent can focus
    on learning the basics: play attacks to deal damage, play defense to block.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each subsequent stage adds a few more cards or a new enemy type. By the time the
    agent reaches Stage 12 with the full card pool and elite enemies, it already has
    a solid foundation of card game fundamentals.
  </p>

  <h2>Automatic Stage Advancement</h2>
  <p>
    The learner monitors the agent's win rate over a rolling window. When it plateaus
    above a threshold, it advances to the next stage. This means the agent spends
    exactly as long as it needs on each difficulty level.
  </p>

